<br>
&quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:blue;">I speak against him, until the day that he comes here and  asks to become a member of the Harvesters <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>on his own accord</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot;<br>
<br>
Those words are on the tip of her tongue, but she does not speak them. After all, the Ilharess seems not to share her sentiments about this. <br>
<br>
Time would have to tell, if he was as reluctant as he seemed, or if he became an asset to the scythe. In the end, even the Enchanter had become an asset after all. Still, she was doubtful. There were differences, yes. The Harvesters were more organized, with more diversity than she had known before. But it still felt like a family. And that is how it should be. And in a family, there were no servants - no unwilling members. <br>
<br>
All these doubts flowed through her mind as she watched them. And despite her fears that this would lead to strife as she had witnessed before, she decides not to intervene. So, instead of speaking them, she turns and steps from the halls without dropping the shadows that cloak her.<br>
<br>
After a moment, all that remains from her presence is a slight chill in the air, and the echo of a whisper: <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;<!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:blue;">All that is left to do is hope.</span><!--EZCODE FONT END-->&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
